avocado <- avocado_df %>%
  mutate(bags = as.numeric(tot_bags == (S_bags + L_bags + XL_bags))) %>%
  mutate(volume = as.numeric(tot_vol == (cat_plu4225 + cat_plu4046 + cat_plu4770)))

Clean the data set

create a total sales columns which is the number of avocados * avg_price

X1: seem to be an id column we can delete it

year: can be extracted from the date, we can delete it

we can separate the date column into day of the week, month, year

seems that all days are mondays so we just need the month

we’ll also remove the region - consumers don’t take to look at item provenance

avocado_trim <- avocado %>%
  mutate(total_sales = (av_price * tot_vol)) %>%
  mutate(other_bags = (tot_bags - (S_bags + L_bags + XL_bags))) %>%
  gather(bag_size, bag_quantity, c(S_bags, L_bags, XL_bags, other_bags)) %>%
  mutate(other_cat = (tot_vol - (cat_plu4046 + cat_plu4225 + cat_plu4770))) %>%
  gather(category, num_avocado, 
         c(cat_plu4046, cat_plu4225, cat_plu4770, other_cat)) %>%
  mutate(month = month(date)) %>%
  mutate(year = (year)) %>%
  select(-c(tot_bags, date, id, bags, volume, av_price, tot_vol, region))

Let’s split the data into train and test

n_data <- nrow(avocado_trim)
test_index <- sample(1:n_data, size = n_data*0.2)

test  <- slice(avocado_trim, test_index)
train <- slice(avocado_trim, -test_index)

Finding the best model Let’s comapre the best models to predict the sales of avocado using the different type of methods:

library(leaps)
regsubsets_forward <- regsubsets(total_sales ~ ., 
                                 data = train, nvmax = 11, 
                                 method = "forward")
sum_regsubsets_forward <- summary(regsubsets_forward)

plot(regsubsets_forward, scale = "bic")

num_avocado - bag_quantity - plu4770 - typeorganic - sizeS_bag - other_cat - year - month - other bag - plu4225 - XL_bags

regsubsets_back <- regsubsets(total_sales ~ ., 
                                 data = train, nvmax = 11, 
                                 method = "backward")
sum_regsubsets_back <- summary(regsubsets_back)

plot(regsubsets_back, scale = "bic")

num_avocado - bag_quantity - plu4770 - typeorganic - sizeS_bag - other_cat - year - other bag - XL_bags -plu 4225 - month

regsubsets_subset <- regsubsets(total_sales ~ ., 
                                 data = train, nvmax = 11, 
                                 method = "exhaustive")
sum_regsubsets_subset <- summary(regsubsets_subset)

plot(regsubsets_subset, scale = "bic")

num_avocado - bag_quantity - plu4770 - typeorganic - sizeS_bag - other_cat - year - other bag - XL_bags -plu 4225 - month

Let’s plot the bic

plot(sum_regsubsets_subset$bic, type = "b")

We can see that 5 parameters should be enough. The first 5 categories are - num_avocado - bag_quantity - plu4770 (category of avocado) - typeorganic - sizeS_bag (ccategory of bags)

library(glmulti) glmulti_fit <- glmulti( total_sales ~ ., data = train, level = 2, # 2 = include pairwise interactions, 1 = main effects only (main effect = no pairwise interactions) minsize = 0, # no min size of model maxsize = 5, # -1 = no max size of model marginality = TRUE, # marginality here means the same as ‘strongly hierarchical’ interactions, i.e. include pairwise interactions only if both predictors present in the model as main effects. method = “g”, # the problem is too large for exhaustive search, so search using a genetic algorithm crit = bic, # criteria for model selection is BIC value (lower is better) plotty = FALSE, # don’t plot models as function runs report = TRUE, # do produce reports as function runs confsetsize = 10, # return best 100 solutions fitfunction = lm # fit using the lm function )

Let’s check how the model performs on the test set

predictions <- predict(mod4_4var, newdata = test)
predict_and_actual <- test %>%
  mutate(predict_sales = predictions) %>%
  mutate(residuals = (sqrt((predict_sales - total_sales) ** 2))) %>%
  select(total_sales, predict_sales, residuals, num_avocado) 

ggplot(predict_and_actual) +
  geom_point(aes(x = num_avocado, y = predict_sales), 
             colour = "blue",
